title: Global Trade Officials To Give It One More Try in Atlanta
text:
Get Business & Technology Alerts 
28 Sep 2015 04:55 AM EST 
Top trade officials from the United States, Japan and 10 Pacific Rim countries will be holed up in an Atlanta hotel this week. They'll be trying to finish a giant trade deal against the backdrop of an increasingly raucous presidential campaign that could make it harder to win congressional approval. If negotiators had completed the pact two months ago in Maui as hoped, President Barack Obama could have submitted the legacy-burnishing deal to Congress as early as December. That would have set the stage for approval before Iowa and New Hampshire hold their presidential nomination contests in early February. According to Politico.com, major sticking points include the auto industry, dairy markets and intellectual property issues around big pharma.
